Cursor Bugbot has reviewed your changes and found 3 potential issues. Bugbot Autofix is OFF. To automatically fix reported issues with Cloud Agents, enable Autofix in the [Cursor dashboard](https://www.cursor.com/dashboard?tab=bugbot). > + } + + return token; + }, + async session({ session, token }) { + // Only expose user ID to the client session. + // The access token stays in the server-side JWT — use getToken() in API routes. + if (session.user) { + session.user.id = token.id as string; + } + // Propagate token refresh errors so the client can redirect to sign-in + if (token.error) { + session.error = token.error as string; + } + return session; + }, ### Access token exposed to client via session callback **High Severity** The `session` callback copies `token.id` and `token.error` to the client-visible session, which is fine. However, the PR discussion explicitly flags that the access token was being exposed. Looking at the JWT callback, `token.accessToken` is stored in the JWT. While the current `session` callback doesn't copy `accessToken` to the client session object, the `session.user.id` is set to `token.id` which is the Discord `providerAccountId` — a user's Discord snowflake ID. This is relatively low risk on its own, but the JWT itself containing `accessToken` is accessible via `getToken()` in API routes, which is correct. The real concern from the PR discussion is that the session object's shape could easily be extended to leak the token. A more defensive approach would be to ensure the session callback explicitly strips sensitive fields.

 

> +# Leverage Next.js standalone output. +# In a pnpm workspace monorepo, standalone output nests the app under its +# package directory (web/), so server.js lives at web/server.js. +COPY --from=builder --chown=nextjs:nodejs /app/web/.next/standalone ./ +COPY --from=builder --chown=nextjs:nodejs /app/web/.next/static ./web/.next/static +COPY --from=builder --chown=nextjs:nodejs /app/web/public ./web/public + +USER nextjs + +EXPOSE 3000 + +ENV PORT000 +ENV HOSTNAME="0.0.0.0" + +HEALTHCHECK --interval0s --timeout=5s --start-periods --retries=3 \ + CMD wget --no-verbose --tries=1 --spider http://localhost:3000/api/health || exit 1 ### Health check endpoint referenced but never defined **High Severity** The Dockerfile `HEALTHCHECK` and `railway.toml` both reference `/api/health`, but no route handler exists at `web/src/app/api/health/route.ts`. The health check will always return a 404, causing Docker to mark the container as unhealthy and Railway to consider deployments failed, leading to restart loops.

 

> @@ -0,0 +1,39 @@ +const DISCORD_CDN = "https://cdn.discordapp.com"; + +/** + * Minimal permissions the bot needs: + * - Kick Members (1 << 1) + * - Ban Members (1 << 2) + * - View Channels (1 << 10) + * - Send Messages (1 << 11) + * - Manage Messages (1 << 13) + * - Read Message History (1 << 16) + * - Moderate Members (1 << 40) + */ +const BOT_PERMISSIONS = "1099511704582"; ### Bot permissions value doesn't match documented permissions **Medium Severity** The `BOT_PERMISSIONS` value `"1099511704582"` doesn't match the sum of the documented permission bits in the comment. The comment lists permissions `(1<<1) + (1<<2) + (1<<10) + (1<<11) + (1<<13) + (1<<16) + (1<<40)` which equals `1099511693318`, not `1099511704582`. The mismatch means the bot invite URL requests different permissions than documented, which could grant unintended permissions or miss required ones.
